text:
Following World War III, all the nations of the world agreed to 50 years of strict isolation from one another in order to prevent additional conflicts. 50 years later, the United States comes out of exile, only to learn that no one else went into isolation.



The story follows a group of soldiers as they try to find out what happened to the other nations of the world. It seems that the other countries stayed in contact with one another. They formed a world government and are now trying to take over the United States. Apparently this had been the goal all along. When the soldiers uncovered this information, they wondered what they should do next. One soldier named George suggested working with the world government, in order to negotiate their continued freedom. The others, however, were not so sure. The other soldiers were former prisoners of war and were still very bitter about the treatment they received while in captivity. They didn't want to kindly negotiate their freedom. "Lets blow up the World Capital," said another soldier named Ted. "We'll show them what we think of their world government." So the majority ruled over the decision and instead of calmly negotiating like George wanted, they decided to use violence. 

The group of soldiers then went to the World Capital and blew it up. This started a war between the United States and the World Government. Since the World Government was so much larger than the United States at this point, they won the war and took control over the United States. Violence didn't help them win, and they should have listened to George, who wanted to work together. The moral of the story is to think before you act, like George would have done.
